Brief profile of company's owner

Starting his career with the export industry in India in the early

1980s, Neeraj Kichlu moved into the distribution, sales and

marketing fields, holding different positions in various companies in

India, dealing with consumer durable products such as desktop

publishing systems, office automation products, computers and

software.

Subse

quently, he worked in Russia from 1993 to 2002, first with a

Singapore based company handling products of Epson, Hewlett

Packard and other brands for Russia and some CIS countries and

then moving to St. Petersburg to develop distribution and marketing

for the entire range of photographic products of the Japanese

company, Konica Corporation. This paved way for a move to Brazil in

2003, when the organization expanded its distribution business to

that country and later also entered manufacturing of products.

Settled in Dub

ai since 2011, he has been connected with the

organizations's real estate business as well as several diversification

projects related to healthcare, solar energy and manufacturing, in

the UAE, South Asia and Russia.

Currently, he is

owner of Aal Jaafar Trading LLC., Dubai, a general

trading and distribution company which works with consumer

durable and FMCG products, working with retailers, wholesalers,

e-commerce segment and customers from Middle East, Africa and

CIS regions.

A well rounded profes

sional, he has over three decades of rich

experience in distribution, trading, international business and new

projects, with hands-on working knowledge in multi country and

multi culture environments.

drive the business of Imperial International LLC:

UAE

A property glut and faltering demand in the Middle

East's business hub had driven prices down by more

than a third since the market peaked some 7 years ago.

The decline had been made worse by the Corona virus

pandemic. The UAE's successful control of the

Covid-19 risk and of proving itself to be open, safe and

connected, is driving businesses and giving confidence

to investors, resulting in a rise in market activity across

all sectors, since Q4-2020. The world's highest

vaccination rate, a host of new company ownership and

visa schemes and a business-friendly environment are

expected to drive economic growth in the UAE, in the

long run. The completion of ongoing infrastructure

INTERNATIONAL

Business potential overview

Russia

Despite the economic crisis caused by the pandemic, the rate of housing

construction in Russia did not fall as much as expected. According to

official statistics agency Rosstat, 75.5 million sqm of residential floor space

was built in Russia in 2020, which is only 5.9 percent less than in 2019. In

order to meet the quotas decreed by the President – the commissioning of

120 million sqm of residential floor space per year – what is being

constructed in Moscow and St. Petersburg will not be enough.

Consequently, the Ministry of Housing, Construction and Utilities, along

with the developers, will be seeking opportunities for speeding up the

construction of new housing, specifically in the regions. It is perfectly

reasonable to expect that in the regions outside the large cities, the mass

market will be a priority for developers in the next two or three years, as

that is where the major demand is concentrated, but developers would

move towards more modern and more cost effective projects. In addition,

the niche market for premium and elite class high end property

developments would continue to exist in the larger cities.

Uzbekistan

Lying on the crossroads of the ancient silk route, Uzbekistan is Central Asia's most

populous country with about 34 million inhabitants. Despite being rich in natural

resources, the country's economy struggled after its independence resulting from the fall

of the USSR empire, with lack of reform, low development and high corruption. However,

this has been rapidly changing under the present Government, due to an aggressive

economic reform programme. In particular, the real estate market had been identified as

one of the key areas of restructuring with the intention to invite foreign investments. The

capital city of Tashkent, with a population of about 2.5 million, has been shortlisted to be

showcased under the government's master plan for its redevelopment by 2041, increasing

its size from 33,000 to 41,500 hectares and redeveloping the city centre to provide a new

business district, high-end residential properties and modern retail and leisure options,

under the Tashkent City Project. The economy has proven to be well diversified on the

export front and resilient in the pandemic period. The reforms and vision of the

government promise to show great progress in the real estate sector – one of the prime

sectors which are the face of progress in Uzbekistan- encouraging foreign investment to

fund its growth. Related developments in this sector are within the retail, hospitality and

tourism sectors which are all poised to multiply rapidly in the coming years.

Business potential overview

Kazakhstan

The real estate market in Kazakhstan is growing, mostly due to state programmes.

Buildings older than 50 years in large city centres are being gradually replaced

with new residential buildings and large shopping malls, especially in the larger

cities of Almaty and Astana.

Unde

r a government scheme recently implemented, a certain category of citizens

were allowed to withdraw the excess amount from their pension fund for certain

limited purposes such as buying property, repaying mortgages, transferring

money to private asset managers and paying for certain healthcare services.

Within less than a month, it is estimated that Kazakhs have withdrawn over $1

billion from the state pension fund as part of this stimulus package, with the vast

majority of people opting for one of the first two options. Property prices in

Kazakhstan jumped 5% in January 2021 in the anticipation of the scheme, official

data shows. An index run by property website Krisha.kz showed a further 3.5%

increase. The scheme has become a boon for developers.

Brazil

After the first year of the Pandemic, the real estate industry in Brazil is still absorbing and reflecting the impacts and changes

caused by COVID-19 and is adapting to the new realities that may arise for all segments of this market. Brazil currently has a

housing deficit of about 8 million dwellings, which is expected to grow to about 12 million by the year 2030. The revitalisation of

the real estate market enables developers to create and develop new products aimed at meeting the new ways of living and

residing resulting from the impact of the pandemic, due to the growing demand for houses in the countryside and in the suburbs,

as people decide to leave the big cities in the pursuit of bigger and more comfortable houses instead of apartments located in

major urban centres.

The real estat

e sector promises to bring good opportunities for local and foreign investors, given the fact

that the local c

urrency has depreciated in comparison to other strong currencies. Another important

development could

be a bill currently in the National Congress which, if approved, will allow investments

to be directed to t

enable national and f

oreign investors to acquire rural real estate properties and will allow foreign

resources to be indirec

tly allocated to rural real estate. This has potential for new developments in the

area, keeping in mind the

language and cultural differences between this Latin American country and

the Middle East or South A

sia.
